87
00:13:38.750 --> 00:13:40.429
Justin Florentine (Besu): Any questions on that?

88
00:13:47.250 --> 00:14:05.439
Justin Florentine (Besu): How do people feel about building on framed transactions or not? So, for example, you may have seen me in the R&D Discord pestering the framed transaction team about, hey, where's your execution specs? Where's the execution specs? They don't have it yet, they're still working on it. Totally understandable, because their thing is just as complex as ours.

89
00:14:05.630 --> 00:14:14.960
Justin Florentine (Besu): And so the question is, it's like, well, what do we, what do we do about that? I hear that Yannick might have an opinion on that matter.

90
00:14:16.640 --> 00:14:21.590
Jannik Luhn: Somewhat, so…

91
00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:38.399
Jannik Luhn: Basically, what we've been thinking about is frame transactions not in the context of the EIP, but in the context of, the encrypted mempool, project that we have going on with Primev, where we build on builder commitments, basically.

92
00:14:39.730 --> 00:14:42.930
Jannik Luhn: so…

93
00:14:44.900 --> 00:15:01.339
Jannik Luhn: Should I give an overview over that? Because it's not really related to the EIP. I don't think it's, it changes anything in the EIP, but maybe, like, at least for me, it was interesting to understand, like, a potential different approach.

94
00:15:01.340 --> 00:15:08.560
Justin Florentine (Besu): appropriate to present a different implementation so we can see how it works and how it, we can learn from it. Would you like to share?

95
00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:15.940
Jannik Luhn: Yep, sure. So, basically, so…

96
00:15:17.690 --> 00:15:41.010
Jannik Luhn: The nice thing about building equipments is that they don't require any protocol changes to Ethereum, so they can be implemented much more quickly than the EIP that we're discussing right now. But on the other hand, it's also way more limited, because the enforcement of the rules is more limited, because we can only rely on slashing, we can't just make blocks illegal or invalid.

97
00:15:41.010 --> 00:15:43.279
Jannik Luhn: Or transactions invalid, or anything like that.

98
00:15:43.580 --> 00:15:58.959
Jannik Luhn: So the kind of naive way we've been… that we've been implementing so far is to, I mean, general process is, the user encrypts their transaction, they send it to a builder, the builder then commits to including it.

99
00:15:59.420 --> 00:16:11.229
Jannik Luhn: once they're committed to including it in the next block, they will receive the key, and then they kind of have to include it in the block if they build it. If they don't do this, or if they build a different block, they get slashed.

100
00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:35.050
Jannik Luhn: The problem there is that the builder does not have a guarantee that they will be able to build the block at all. They might lose the auction, and also they might just give the transaction, once they have it, to another party, to another builder. They might then build the block, and since they are not participating in this protocol, they're not staked, they can include or front-front their transaction without getting slashed.

101
00:16:35.590 --> 00:16:49.579
Jannik Luhn: And we can't even slash the original builder who forwarded the transaction, who leaked the transaction, because it could have also been the user itself. So there's kind of a non-attributable problem there.

102
00:16:50.150 --> 00:16:52.999
Jannik Luhn: So… that's why…

103
00:16:53.000 --> 00:17:11.769
Jannik Luhn: at least I was not particularly happy with this protocol, but now I've looked a little bit into frame transactions and realized that we can actually do quite a bit of enforcement there of these rules, because frame transactions do allow us to make transactions invalid, according to custom rules that we can define.

104
00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:15.479
Jannik Luhn: And the rules that we need are actually quite simple,

105
00:17:15.480 --> 00:17:26.409
Jannik Luhn: we just, require two signatures, basically. The user has to sign the transaction, and the builder has to sign the transaction. And since, kind of, both parties have to sign off,

106
00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:36.150
Jannik Luhn: Yeah, passing the transaction or giving the transaction to someone else is not, not possible anymore, because, yeah, then we could slash the original builder.

107
00:17:38.430 --> 00:17:41.190
Justin Florentine (Besu): Are there any links to this design that you could share?

108
00:17:41.580 --> 00:17:50.970
Jannik Luhn: Not yet. We haven't written it down properly yet, but I can, I can write it down and send it around, I guess.

109
00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:53.610
Jannik Luhn: Yeah, and…

110
00:17:53.610 --> 00:18:00.689
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yeah, if you wouldn't mind, I think that would be helpful. I'd love to run that by Anders, also, and see if it gives him any ideas.

111
00:18:01.610 --> 00:18:09.159
Jannik Luhn: Yeah, in general, what may surprise me about this is that there are actually quite a bit of rules that we can define now,

112
00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:26.889
Jannik Luhn: in code, outside of the protocol, and that might be interesting in the AP. I don't think… yeah, I don't have a good enough understanding of the API to evaluate if there are things we can outsource, basically, but maybe Anders has thoughts about this.

113
00:18:28.050 --> 00:18:36.390
Gottfried Herold: Yeah, actually, I may have a bit of a question about, regarding the relationship to freight transactions from someone who actually, understands the AIP quite, quite a lot.

114
00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:48.160
Gottfried Herold: I mean, in the, actual, Lucid EIP, we have basically two things that go on-chain. One is the transaction ticket, and the other thing is sort of the individual transaction, after, sort of, it gets decrypted.

115
00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:57.400
Gottfried Herold: So in the context of frame transactions, what do you want to sort of build upon atop the frame transactions? The actual, ST ticket?

116
00:18:57.480 --> 00:18:59.610
Gottfried Herold: Or the decrypted transaction.

117
00:18:59.790 --> 00:19:04.809
Gottfried Herold: Because, from my point of view, I mean, the latter is kind of…

118
00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:08.250
Gottfried Herold: Easy, but does not give us as much?

119
00:19:09.040 --> 00:19:20.080
Gottfried Herold: The much more interesting but rather difficult part is more the first part, where basically you have the, sealed ticket, which, as of now, is only part of the,

120
00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:31.670
Gottfried Herold: of the beacon block, but not much of the execution part, which is a bit problematic in the sense that the Timeliness Committee actually has to

121
00:19:31.890 --> 00:19:38.219
Gottfried Herold: Or basically make some unpaid-for, as of now, validity check.

122
00:19:38.780 --> 00:19:50.440
Gottfried Herold: that is sort of related to the PTC votes and also to attester votes, based on the validity of these, entries there. And if… I mean, it would be very, very helpful to actually allow for some kind of…

123
00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:57.879
Gottfried Herold: Well, customizable authentication mechanism there, and to be frank, if we ever want to go post-quantum, we actually need this.

124
00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:07.970
Gottfried Herold: But sort of having here something that is much more heavy, is potentially a bit problematic, I think.

125
00:20:08.350 --> 00:20:10.880
Gottfried Herold: I'm not sure whether there's any ideas regarding that.

126
00:20:15.100 --> 00:20:20.490
Justin Florentine (Besu): I had not considered it. This is… I, I think…

127
00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:21.010
Gottfried Herold: I think…

128
00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:27.860
Justin Florentine (Besu): Yeah, I mean, I see what you mean by, you kind of really need to be, you know, both the ticket and the plain text transaction need to be on.

129
00:20:27.860 --> 00:20:39.690
Gottfried Herold: I mean… I mean, the transaction is kind of the easy part, I mean, easy comparably, and there's kind of clear what you would have to do, but I think the much more interesting part is the ticket, because right now we basically enshrine the…

130
00:20:39.990 --> 00:20:50.719
Gottfried Herold: Right now, the EARP basically enshrines the usual litter curve-based signature that we have on the ticket part, and this is kind of the lightweight part of the protocol, by design.

131
00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:51.170
Justin Florentine (Besu): It ends.

132
00:20:51.170 --> 00:20:51.550
Gottfried Herold: And…

133
00:20:52.080 --> 00:20:55.130
Justin Florentine (Besu): But it's also the early part of it, right?

134
00:20:55.130 --> 00:20:55.730
Gottfried Herold: The what?

135
00:20:55.730 --> 00:21:03.510
Justin Florentine (Besu): It's also the early part of it. It's how we are able to kind of get out in front of when the plain text transaction needs to be executed, and make sure that the.

136
00:21:03.510 --> 00:21:04.300
Gottfried Herold: Exactly.

137
00:21:04.300 --> 00:21:06.490
Justin Florentine (Besu): Exactly. Exactly.

138
00:21:06.490 --> 00:21:24.320
Gottfried Herold: But for this, it's actually… I mean, frank transactions are actually much more useful, also, for this part, not just… I mean, first of all, it's the security part, because we want to have some kind of quantum part. The other thing is that an actual correct usage of Lucid would, in fact, in order to hide,

139
00:21:24.400 --> 00:21:28.359
Gottfried Herold: Sender, identity, which is something you absolutely want for,

140
00:21:28.560 --> 00:21:40.400
Gottfried Herold: To protect against, probabilistic front-running attacks, you would actually have to make sure that your, the ticket is actually sent from an… and from an address that is unlinkable to the one that is actually doing the transaction.

141
00:21:40.410 --> 00:21:53.659
Gottfried Herold: So, essentially, correct usage of Lucid would mean that you make some stealth, or Tornado Cash, or Railgun, or whatever transaction first to some other sort of temporary, one-time

142
00:21:54.130 --> 00:22:00.650
Gottfried Herold: Paymaster, basically, let's call it, and then use that one to sort of send your, ticket.

143
00:22:00.700 --> 00:22:07.539
